1-"
\f1\fs26 \cb2 Draw a random object and divide it up in as many triangles as you can (32 degree) [TT]
\f0\fs24 \cb1 "\
\
Commentary: I was looking at my guitar so I decided to dash off a guitar (although it ends up looking more like a banjo or an apple with a stick in it). It turns out 5 minutes is not that long, at least when it comes to trying to reduce even a relatively small drawing down to as great a number of triangles as possible; as you can see, I didn't get too far (see photo). This is an interesting case study of what it means to be a rule, as there's not much specificity provided. "A random object" could be anything (what would a computer make of that? As a side note, see the great book 10 Print and its notes about "randomness" in computing). I don't know what "32 degree" means so I ignored that part. There's no guidance given about what sort of triangle to draw either. I found myself making my own efficiency rules - e.g. I drew right triangles where space allowed because they are easiest to draw, and I got into a rhythm where I'd split a triangle to generate two smaller triangles, then drop a line from each of their hypotenuses to create yet more right triangles, and drop a line from those, and so on. Approaching the outside of the rounded body of the guitar was interesting because it resembles how a computer draws a circle - an ever increasingly large number of straight lines decreasing in individual sides, which approaches (but never reaches) the limit of curvature.\
\
