Commentary: OK, this one was interesting, but if it's hard to write instructions on drawing, it's even harder to write instructions on building (see any furniture assembly instructions ever). It was pretty clear from the get-go that this would be a paper airplane when assembled but only because I've made them before. Certain instructions are not clear initially - for instance step 2 doesn't say how far inward you should fold the corner, and it's only when you read step 3 and figure out what it's saying that you realize you're supposed to fold each corner as far as half the width of the page (see the first photo). The references to rotating triangles on their axes were confusing, too. I got really confused around step 8 and am not at all sure that I assembled this correctly (see second photo). This might explain its rather disappointing flight (see video). Then again I've always been bad at paper airplanes\'85 Also it seems a shame not to indicate at least at the end that this is a paper airplane and may be thrown to glide (or crash). The instructions mention wings but that's not enough indication of the intent of the piece.\
