3-"
\f1\fs26 \cb3 Draw a circle using only horizontal lines
\f0\fs24 \cb1 "\
\
Commentary: this one took all of 30 seconds (see photo). I sort of got at this with the first example (of making triangles out of a rounded guitar body and approaching a limit of curvature). That said, I came into this with assumptions about the context and what is meant by "horizontal lines." It occurs to me I replaced "horizontal" in my head with "straight" - not the same. I'd better do another. \'85 Well, it's an ugly circle (see second photo), but it gets the point across. Maybe it's a mistake for me to assess these instructions on how well a computer would interpret them. Any human would understand this one pretty easily, I think.\
\
4-"
\f1\fs26 \cb4 Step 1: Draw a large square on a piece paper with a pen. Mark the midpoints of each side of the square and draw the connecting lines. Step 2: Mark 4 points at 1/3 the length of the side of the new square and connect the lines. Repeat steps 1 and 2 in a loop until there is no more room to draw.\'a0 [JP]
\f0\fs24 \cb1 "\
\
Commentary: I had to get a pen out for this one. "Draw the connecting lines" is ambiguous - do I connect the adjacent points or the opposite points or both? I connected both but I think given the remaining context probably I was only supposed to connect the adjacent ones. Step 3 is a bit confusing in its phrasing - should I mark four points on each side of the new square? or is it one point on each side, for a total of four points? the latter makes more sense so I did that - but then it's smooth sailing. It did not take five minutes to run out of room - I got into a rhythm. A nice varying looping pattern. I look at the result and get a little vertigo (see picture).\
